# ADR-0001: Framework and Deployment Platform

## Status

Accepted

## Context

{{ display_name }} is a **{{ site_type }}** site. The team needed to choose a static site framework and a deployment platform.

Key requirements:

- Static output: no server runtime in production
- Fast builds suitable for a content-heavy repository
- Good developer experience with hot reload
{% if site_type == "docs" %}
- Native support for content collections or a similar structured content model
- Good Markdown/MDX support including custom components in content
{% elif site_type == "blog" %}
- Tag and category taxonomy pages
- RSS feed generation
- Author pages
{% elif site_type == "landing-page" %}
- Component-based page building
- Image optimisation built in or easy to add
- Fast build times for iteration speed
{% elif site_type == "portfolio" %}
- Content collections for project entries
- Flexible layout system for varied project showcases
{% endif %}
- Deployment that supports preview URLs for pull requests
- Free tier suitable for the expected traffic level

### Frameworks Considered

| Framework | Pros | Cons |
|-----------|------|------|
| Astro | Zero-JS by default, islands architecture, excellent content collections, framework-agnostic components | Relatively new, smaller ecosystem than Next.js |
| Next.js (static export) | Large ecosystem, React components, well-understood | Static export has limitations vs full Next.js; heavier JS baseline |
| Hugo | Extremely fast builds, mature, no Node.js runtime | Go templating has a learning curve; limited JavaScript integration |
| Eleventy | Flexible, minimal opinions, excellent template language choice | More configuration required; smaller community than Astro or Hugo |

### Deployment Platforms Considered

| Platform | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| Vercel | Excellent DX, instant preview URLs, generous free tier, framework-aware | Vendor lock-in risk for advanced features |
| Netlify | Strong free tier, flexible build plugins, good form/function support | Slightly slower deploys than Vercel |
| GitHub Pages | Zero cost, simple setup, no third-party account needed | No built-in preview URLs; limited build environment |
| Cloudflare Pages | Global CDN, generous free tier, fast cache invalidation | Newer platform; some build environment differences |

## Decision

We chose **{{ framework }}** as the framework and **{{ deploy_target }}** as the deployment platform.

### Framework Rationale

{% if framework == "astro" %}
Astro was chosen because:

- Content collections provide typed, validated frontmatter out of the box
- Zero JavaScript shipped by default - pages are pure HTML unless a component explicitly opts in
- Islands architecture allows selective hydration: interactive widgets load JS, everything else does not
- Supports `.astro`, `.md`, `.mdx`, and framework components (React, Vue, Svelte) in the same project
- Build performance is excellent even with many pages
{% elif framework == "nextjs-static" %}
Next.js static export was chosen because:

- The team has existing React expertise - no new framework syntax to learn
- The React ecosystem provides a wide range of ready-made components
- Static export (`output: 'export'`) produces fully portable static HTML
- Image optimisation is built in via `next/image`
- TypeScript support is first-class
{% elif framework == "hugo" %}
Hugo was chosen because:

- Build speed is unmatched - thousands of pages in seconds
- No Node.js dependency makes the build environment simpler
- Mature and stable: breaking changes are rare
- Built-in taxonomy, pagination, RSS, and sitemap generation
- Shortcodes provide reusable content snippets without JavaScript
{% elif framework == "eleventy" %}
Eleventy was chosen because:

- Template language agnostic: Markdown, Nunjucks, Liquid, and JavaScript templates can coexist
- Minimal magic - the build pipeline is explicit and easy to understand
- Excellent support for data files and computed data
- No framework lock-in: the output is plain HTML, easy to migrate later
- Active community and plugin ecosystem
{% endif %}

### Deployment Rationale

{% if deploy_target == "vercel" %}
Vercel was chosen because:

- Automatic preview deployments for every pull request provide quick visual review
- Zero-config deployment: the framework is detected automatically
- The edge CDN delivers consistent performance globally
- The free tier covers the expected traffic without cost
{% elif deploy_target == "netlify" %}
Netlify was chosen because:

- Deploy previews on every pull request support the content review workflow
- Build plugins provide flexibility for custom build steps (link checking, image optimisation)
- The free tier is generous and well-suited to static sites
- Form handling and serverless functions are available if needed later
{% elif deploy_target == "github-pages" %}
GitHub Pages was chosen because:

- No third-party account is required - everything is in the existing GitHub repository
- Cost is zero (included with the repository)
- The GitHub Actions workflow gives full control over the build and deployment process
- Suitable for the expected traffic and team size
{% elif deploy_target == "cloudflare-pages" %}
Cloudflare Pages was chosen because:

- Deployment to Cloudflare's global network provides very low latency worldwide
- The free tier is among the most generous available
- Automatic preview deployments are supported
- Integration with Cloudflare Workers is available if edge functions are needed later
{% endif %}

## Consequences

### Positive

- Clear, documented technical foundation from day one
- Framework and deployment choice are aligned with the project's {{ site_type }} use case
- Preview deployments on every PR support an async review workflow
- Static output means no server to maintain or secure

### Negative

{% if framework == "astro" %}
- Astro's `.astro` component syntax is not transferable to other frameworks
- The content collections API has had breaking changes between major versions
{% elif framework == "nextjs-static" %}
- Static export disables some Next.js features (server actions, API routes, image optimisation without a custom loader)
- React adds baseline JavaScript weight compared to zero-JS frameworks
{% elif framework == "hugo" %}
- Go template syntax has a steeper learning curve for developers from JavaScript backgrounds
- Adding interactivity requires separate JavaScript, as Hugo has no component model
{% elif framework == "eleventy" %}
- More initial configuration is required compared to opinionated frameworks
- No built-in image optimisation (a plugin is required)
{% endif %}

### Risks and Mitigations

- **Framework major version upgrades**: Breaking changes are possible. Mitigate by pinning the framework version in `package.json` and reviewing release notes before upgrading.
- **Deployment platform pricing changes**: Static files are portable. The build output can be hosted anywhere. Mitigate by keeping the build config simple and avoiding platform-specific features where possible.
- **Build time growth as content scales**: Monitor build times in CI. If they exceed 10 minutes, investigate incremental builds or content pagination strategies.

